text:
It was perhaps fitting that Munich was the site of the Trump Administration‚Äôs dramatic appeasement of the Kremlin dictator, when the Vice President attacked our western allies, and the Defense Secretary weakened our NATO alliance.

In going so far as to parrot Putin‚Äôs false talking points and to blame Ukraine for being invaded and brutalized by Russia, Trump has undermined Ukraine‚Äôs position in potential negotiations with Russia and compromised our own national security interests.  

In one week, President Trump‚Äôs glaring weakness has done more damage to 80 years of bipartisan U.S. global leadership than all our adversaries could do, combined. 

We must ensure Ukraine receives the support and assistance it needs to defend itself against Russia‚Äôs unprovoked war, not leave this country to fend for itself.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1942, Lt. Edward O'Hare, a U.S. Navy fighter pilot aboard the aircraft carrier  ùêøùëíùë•ùëñùëõùëîùë°ùëúùëõ, became America‚Äôs first WWII flying ace. 

Rabaul, a key Japanese stronghold in Papua New Guinea, had been heavily fortified with airbases and posed a threat to the Solomon Islands. The ùêøùëíùë•ùëñùëõùëîùë°ùëúùëõ was tasked with a bombing raid on Rabaul, but as the ship sailed toward the target, radar detected Japanese bombers approaching. 

O'Hare, piloting an F4F Wildcat, quickly engaged and shot down five Japanese G4M1 Betty bombers in just four minutes, halting the attack and earning the title of "ace." Although the raid on Rabaul was canceled, O'Hare‚Äôs bravery earned him the Medal of Honor, and in 1949, Chicago‚Äôs airport was named in his honor.

We will use every lever and every vote at our disposal, regardless of the personal or political consequences.  This matter is that time-sensitive and it is that existential.  It is legacy-defining.  

We all want an immediate end to this brutal Russian invasion and killing.  For a peace agreement to be fair and lasting, it must be done in a way that holds the Russian invaders accountable, protects the dignity of the Ukrainian victims, and provides for fair and equitable cost-sharing amongst all European nations.  To do otherwise would be to encourage future invasions and to perpetuate future heartache and bloodshed.  

This is about Peace Through Strength.  This is about Patriotic Common Sense.  And Patriotic Common Sense is what America must always stand for.

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
MAGA NATION, this post is for you, please read.

I know you because I‚Äôm one of you and we delivered a mandate which is President Trump‚Äôs America First agenda - the agenda he campaigned on at every rally he held and we attended across the country. 

Congress has to deliver that mandate with our budget reconciliation process, but some in Congress are developing amnesia to the very fact that YOU, the people, did not vote for them and their agenda, YOU voted for Trump and HIS agenda.

President Trump and his great team are delivering his campaign promises at record speed through his executive orders and DOGE.

President Trump is slashing regulations, destroying DEI, making the world respect America again through reciprocal tariffs, is in the process of ending world wars and America paying for them, has secured the border and begun deportations, is reducing the over bloated government workforce, and with Elon‚Äôs DOGE - they are literally exposing and dismantling the deep state‚Äôs government money laundering and out right fraud!  It‚Äôs been an AMAZING first month.

But we in Congress now have to deliver as well.

With the historic election. You would think Republicans would just whip up our bills, budget, and approps and pass them with ease, but nope, it‚Äôs so much harder than it should be.

President Trump wants one big beautiful bill and I prefer one as well, but we have to make sure HIS agenda is in that one big beautiful bill and there are a few items that some of my conservative colleagues don‚Äôt support. (Conservative doesn‚Äôt mean they supported Trump until they had to)

No Tax on Tips, No Tax on Overtime, and No Tax on Social Security were President Trump‚Äôs big campaign promises and some conservatives don‚Äôt want to include those when we renew the tax law - Trump‚Äôs Tax Cuts and Jobs Act. 

Those tax campaign promises help many Americans that need it the most as they have been hit hard by Biden and the Democrat‚Äôs high inflation over the past 4 years.  We are talking about senior‚Äôs and workers. 

So why, you ask, would some conservatives not support no tax on tips, overtime, and social security???

It‚Äôs because they are singularly focused on deeply cutting spending and some of them never supported Trump in the first place so they have no respect for the people‚Äôs mandate. Some of them simply don‚Äôt get it. And some of them think overly highly of themselves and their own plan.

Here is what they are missing, as well as some others in our Republican conference. 

With spending cuts, DOGE cuts, Trump‚Äôs de-regs, Trump‚Äôs reciprocal tariffs, energy policies, we MUST renew TCJA WITH all of the no tax campaign promises because ALL OF THIS together will be like Elon‚Äôs rockets to our economy!!!

And it all will work together to drive revenue AND cut spending AND will deliver the mandate THE PEOPLE voted for!!!

Cutting spending is only one piece and believe me I‚Äôm all for it, but with our compounding interest now bigger than our military budget, we can‚Äôt cut our way out of this.

We have to increase revenue but not be so blind and stupid that we give tax breaks to corporations but NOT to desperately suffering workers and seniors!!!

Give money back to workers and seniors and they will spend it into the economy and will be thanking Republicans at the same time!!!

Increasing revenue will happen through reciprocal tariffs, killing the green new deal handouts and tax breaks and driving American energy (which will lower business cost and inflation), cutting the strangling regulations on businesses, and DOGE‚Äôs lethal attack on the deep state‚Äôs money laundering and fraud.

But for the love of God, help the people that need it most, get out of your own way, deliver TRUMP‚ÄôS agenda, and maybe just maybe we will win the midterms if we do this right.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
The world mourns in anguish today as four more hostages‚ÄîOded Lifshitz, Shiri Bibas, and her two little boys, Kfir and Ariel‚Äîare returned home to Israel today. A peace activist. A mother. Two innocent children. Ripped from their home, subjected to unimaginable terror, and murdered in cold blood.
 
Kfir was just nine months old on October 7th. His life‚Äîalong with so many others‚Äîwas stolen in an act of unthinkable evil. Their loss is a tragic reminder of the true cost of Hamas‚Äôs barbarism. We owe it to the victims and their families to stand unwavering in the pursuit of justice.
 
This is not just Israel‚Äôs fight‚Äîit is the fight of every nation that upholds freedom, justice, and human dignity. The United States stands unequivocally with Israel‚Äîtoday, tomorrow, and always. Every hostage must be brought home. Every innocent life must be honored. And every terrorist must face the full weight of justice.
 
Terror will never prevail because we will never waver. We stand shoulder to shoulder with our allies, and together, we will see justice done, freedom upheld, and light triumph over darkness.

üö® REP. ROY STATEMENT ON KASH PATEL CONFIRMATION üö®

I am pleased that ‚Äî after too much delay ‚Äî the Senate has confirmed Kash Patel today as Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation.

Americans across the country have lost faith in the bureau's ability to fulfill its mission to the American people and the Constitution. Instead of targeting real criminals and public safety threats, FBI leadership has been focused for too long on politicized witch hunts ranging from President Trump and his team to concerned parents like my friend Scott Smith and pro-life Americans like Mark Houck.

As a former federal prosecutor and First Assistant Attorney General of Texas, it‚Äôs important to me that Director Patel has made clear his mission to serve as the disruptor America needs at the FBI. ¬†He is poised to end the corruption, politicization, and weaponization that have taken the FBI away from its designated mission ‚Äî much of which has exploded in the post 9/11 drift toward loose definitions of domestic terrorism that have moved the department off the path of combatting organized crime across state lines. I look forward to working with Director Patel to keep Americans safe and put more bad guys in jail.

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text:
I will oppose Kash Patel‚Äôs confirmation to serve as Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation. The FBI‚Äôs mission is ‚Äúto protect the American people and uphold the Constitution of the United States.‚Äù Mr. Patel and I agree the bureau has crept past that mission, become an increasingly political agency, and eroded the public‚Äôs trust. We have had multiple frank and open discussions about how best to restore that trust. I agree with Mr. Patel that it begins by getting agents out in the field, doing what they signed up to do, rather than sitting behind an administrative desk.

My reservations with Mr. Patel stem from his own prior political activities and how they may influence his leadership. The FBI must be trusted as the federal agency that roots out crime and corruption, not focused on settling political scores. I have been disappointed that when he had the opportunity to push back on the administration‚Äôs decision to force the FBI to provide a list of agents involved in the January 6 investigations and prosecutions, he failed to do so.

If confirmed, I wish him a successful tenure at the helm of this agency, and will endeavor to work with him to help address issues in Alaska, improve Tribal law enforcement across the country, and make needed changes within the FBI. I truly hope that he proves me wrong about the reservations I have of him today.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The first anti-freeze order invalidated the Trump OMB freeze directive; so OMB withdrew the directive itself, while maintaining the freeze policy¬†in place.¬†Many judges would disapprove of that kind of bad-faith trickery around a court order, so stand by.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The AGs returned to the court and succeeded at getting a general order mandating compliance with the original broad anti-freeze order.¬†But the Trumpsters in the ‚ÄúFog Bank‚Äù are still holding obligated funds frozen, just not explicitly saying so.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The ‚ÄúFog Bank‚Äù method was to go incommunicado to funds recipients, or be unable to answer questions, or give vague and evasive non-responses:¬†give no hard refusals a court order or contempt finding could attach to, but send no funding either.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The attorneys general then in another court got a broad-ranging anti-freeze order directing pages and pages of agency defendants to halt the freeze.¬†So Trumpsters withdrew into the ‚ÄúFog Bank‚Äù ‚Äî no one outright defied the order, but the illegal freeze kept on.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: As litigation gets to discovery and deposition, it will become clear whether the ‚ÄúFog Bank‚Äù was deliberate contempt of court, and by whom.¬†I expect that Trumpsters, like KGB officers in Soviet agencies, are inside the agencies enforcing the ‚ÄúFog Bank.‚Äù

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: In the meantime, where specific legal pretexts can be found to freeze certain funding under a new theory, they‚Äôre using the pretexts.¬†Where they have no pretext, the ‚ÄúFog Bank‚Äù strategy of silent contumacy persists.

Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
This budget resolution is a complete game changer when it comes to securing our border and making our military more lethal. It will allow President Trump to fulfill the promises he made to the American people ‚Äî a very big deal.

As Senate Budget Committee Chairman, I‚Äôm incredibly pleased by the discipline shown by my Senate Republican colleagues to ensure that the most transformational border security bill in history can soon become a reality.

This budget resolution allows the Judiciary and Homeland Security Committees to spend up to $175 billion in total to implement President Trump‚Äôs border security agenda. It instructs the Armed Services Committee to spend up to $150 billion to make our military more lethal. It also allocates up to $20 billion to be spent to modernize the Coast Guard.

It does not direct how money will be spent ‚Äî it only sets a number.

This budget resolution directs other Senate committees to find spending cuts to fully pay for the much-needed funding for border security and the U.S. military.

I hope the House can pass one big bill that meets President Trump‚Äôs priorities. But this approach provides money that we needed yesterday to continue the momentum on securing our border, enforcing our immigration laws, and rebuilding our military. Time is of the essence.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1948, NASCAR was founded, marking the beginning of what would become one of America‚Äôs most popular spectator sports and a multi-billion-dollar industry.

The organization was founded by William ‚ÄúBill‚Äù France Sr. Early races featured mostly stock cars like Buicks and Oldsmobiles with minor modifications. The Daytona 500 was first run in 1959, with Lee Petty claiming the victory. His son, Richard Petty, would go on to dominate NASCAR, winning the Daytona 500 a record seven times.

In 1972, Bill France Sr.‚Äôs son began transforming NASCAR from a regional sport into a global phenomenon. Under his leadership, NASCAR secured sponsorships and TV deals, solidifying its place as a major sport in America and worldwide.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First¬†

Deanna Gardner, a resident of Oxford, is the founder and leader of Mother Love, Inc., a nonprofit organization dedicated to addressing food insecurity and homelessness in her community. With 15 years of experience in community outreach, Deanna's efforts have provided essential meals, resources, and employment opportunities to those in need.

Her nonprofit operates "Blessing Boxes" to ensure daily access to food, distributes care packages to the homeless, and organizes events such as Halloween costume giveaways, a Christmas drive, and a prom drive that offers donated dresses and tuxedos.

Deanna's commitment has fostered a strong sense of community involvement, motivating others to assist those in need. Named after her husband‚Äôs mother, the organization‚Äôs name, Mother Love, represents a profound commitment to serving and supporting the community. Through Mother Love, Deanna continues to make a meaningful impact.

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share remarkable stories from across our district‚Äîstories of people who rise above the ordinary and remind us of the power of kindness, connection, and community. This week, we honor a man who has spent a lifetime doing just that. A man who needs no introduction but certainly deserves our recognition. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero: Doug Turner.
 
At 87 years old, Doug Turner has spent his life in service‚Äîto his country as a U.S. Army veteran, to our land as a 30-year U.S. Forest Service worker, and to our community as an artist, a storyteller, and a neighbor in the truest sense of the word. Along with his late wife Susan‚Äîwho served as Newtown Borough Council President‚ÄîDoug dedicated himself to the town they called home, whether teaching students at Goodnoe Elementary about the importance of trees or helping organize Newtown‚Äôs annual Arbor Day celebration. 
 
In 2022, when Doug lost Susan, he found a way to keep their shared spirit of giving alive‚Äîby bringing people together. He started hosting an annual winter party, a simple gathering meant to combat the isolation of winter and rekindle the warmth of true neighborly connection. No guest list, no expectations. Just an open door and one request: ‚ÄúBring only a smile.‚Äù
 
This year, however, something remarkable happened. A simple act‚Äîan old-fashioned, handwritten, hand-delivered invitation‚Äîdidn‚Äôt just bring together a neighborhood; it brought together the world. Doug's invitation scribbled on a paper snowflake with his signature humor, "From 4 p.m. to whenever the cops come,‚Äù captured hearts from Alaska to Australia. Inspired by Doug, people everywhere started throwing their own neighborhood parties, making a conscious effort to reach out to those around them. What Doug started in his corner of Newtown rippled throughout the world, proving that one person can ignite a movement of kindness‚Äîone, in this case, that went viral.
 
So today, we celebrate Doug‚Äînot for a viral party, but for showing us that in a world often divided, there is still more that unites us than separates us. For reminding us that we are not just individuals living side by side but neighbors‚Äîmeant to share in life‚Äôs joys, lift each other in hardship, and find strength in one another.
 
Thank you, Doug, for showing us that community is built through kindness, strengthened by connection, and made whole when we come together.

Name: LaMalfa, Doug
text:
I joined @RepThompson  in introducing the Pacific Flyway Enhancement Act. This bill allows the Secretary of Agriculture to enroll additional agricultural lands in the Conservation Reserve Enhancement Program as long as it is necessary to address wetland habitat concerns, and encourages farmers to manage their working croplands in ways that support wetland-dependent species by permitting seasonal flooding of these fields.

Drought is always just around the corner, and we have to make the most of the water we get to benefit farms, people, and wildlife. Even in a better water year, poor water policies hurt both farmers and wildlife. This bill helps protect both by supporting agriculture and the hundreds of species that rely on the Pacific Flyway. It‚Äôs a common-sense, bipartisan approach to keeping habitats intact and land productive.

text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1732, George Washington was born in Westmoreland County, Virginia.

He joined the British army during the French and Indian War, where he gained leadership experience. After the war, he returned to manage his plantation, Mount Vernon. Washington became active in the Virginia House of Burgesses and later joined the Continental Congress. In 1775, he was appointed commander of the Continental Army.

In 1789, Washington became the first U.S. president, setting precedents for future leaders. However, he disliked politics and resigned after two terms.

Washington passed away in 1799, identifying himself as George Washington, of Mount Vernon, a citizen of the United States.

The first picture is the sign of the village of Nir Oz, which was founded in 1955 by Oded Lifshitz and others, his body was returned this week. The next picture is the home of the Bibas family. The bodies of Shiri Bibas and her sons Ariel, who was four, and Kfir, who was nine months old, were returned this week.

All the lives lost on that dark day deserved to be able to grow old with their loved ones and live a full life. The victims of October 7th will forever live in our hearts and the pain will never be forgotten.

Last night at the Pentagon, President Trump and Secretary Hegseth dismantled a core principle of American democracy: the apolitical military.

Let me explain what‚Äôs going on and why it is deeply dangerous for our country: üßµ

Name: Sherrill, Mikie
text: Secretary Hegseth announced that he is firing some of our nation‚Äôs top military leaders ‚Äî including Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff General C.Q. Brown, Chief of Naval Operations Admiral Lisa Franchetti, and a number of three and four star Generals and Flag Officers. (2/9)

Name: Sherrill, Mikie
text: You don‚Äôt rise to our military‚Äôs highest positions without decades of leadership and commitment to serving missions across the globe. Four-star General C.Q. Brown has been serving our nation since 1984. Four-star Admiral Lisa Franchetti has been serving since 1985. Both of these individuals earned their barrier-breaking positions because they devoted their lives to taking on our nation‚Äôs toughest challenges ‚Äî and they have the resumes to prove it. (3/9)

Name: Sherrill, Mikie
text: Yet, Secretary Hegseth called Admiral Franchetti a DEI hire in his book, and criticized General Brown because of his commitment to promoting diversity in our armed forces. This move isn‚Äôt about strengthening our armed forces, and it isn‚Äôt about merit. It's about Pete Hegseth and Donald Trump implementing their political agenda. (4/9)

Name: Sherrill, Mikie
text: Additionally, Trump and Hegseth fired the top Judge Advocates General, who are the military‚Äôs top lawyers. These are the individuals who interpret law for our commanders, and ensure that we‚Äôre fighting in accordance with our values. (5/9)

Name: Sherrill, Mikie
text: Now, Trump and Hegseth are trying to gut the military‚Äôs leadership so they can use the armed forces to carry out their personal, political agenda. This move will threaten America‚Äôs national security, show weakness to dictators worldwide like Vladimir Putin, and give Donald Trump unchecked power to abuse our military. (7/9)

Name: Sherrill, Mikie
text: Normally, our military‚Äôs top leadership serves under multiple administrations ‚Äî Democrats and Republicans alike. At the beginning of a presidential term, the leaders in these positions typically stay in place ‚Äî some of the leaders fired yesterday even served in Trump‚Äôs first administration. (6/9)

Name: Sherrill, Mikie
text: In the United States Armed Forces, you swear an oath to the Constitution ‚Äî not a person, not a political party. It‚Äôs an oath I took for the first time at age eighteen when I entered the Naval Academy, and have taken numerous times throughout my career. I will never abandon that oath, and I will always fight to protect the men and women who risk their lives to serve our country. (9/9)

Name: Hirono, Mazie K.
text:
President Trump‚Äôs decision to fire¬†General CQ Brown, Admiral Lisa Franchetti, General James Slife, and the senior uniformed attorneys of the Army, Navy, and Air Force is an incredibly reckless decision that dangerously politicizes our military and undermines our national security, military readiness, and the rule of law, ultimately making Americans less safe.¬†

These senior leaders have faithfully and apolitically served our country for decades, providing exactly what the Constitution expects of them - their best military advice to civilian leadership. There is no reasonable justification for these terminations. Instead, the dismissals reveal the President‚Äôs true intention - installing a group of ‚Äúyes men‚Äù with fealty to him and not the Constitution¬†or the American people. It‚Äôs also revealing that General Brown and Admiral Franchetti, both fired, are the only person of color and woman, respectively, serving on the Joint Chiefs of Staff.¬†

The firings of each of the Services‚Äô senior uniformed legal advisors is particularly troubling¬†and completely unprecedented. These nonpartisan attorneys serve continuously in both Republican and Democratic administrations, without fear or favor. Our military leaders rely on them to provide their best legal advice, regardless of party.¬†¬†It‚Äôs clear these individuals were singled out to ensure their successors understood that only the President‚Äôs expansive and legally dubious interpretations of military law would be tolerated. Ultimately, these dismissals will have a chilling effect on the willingness of uniformed attorneys to speak truth to power, undermining the rule of law.

At a time of global uncertainty, we need steady, experienced leadership at the highest levels of our military. ¬†While President Trump and Secretary Hegseth have claimed repeatedly they want the military to focus solely on ‚Äúlethality,‚Äù firing senior leaders willing to push back and installing ‚Äúyes men‚Äù in their place will have the opposite effect. My Republican colleagues say they care about the military and are willing to spend billions more to increase lethality, but shamefully put their heads in the sand as the President threatens the foundation of our military and our democracy with these unprecedented firings. Now is the time for all of my colleagues, Republican and Democrat, to prove they really care about the military by pushing back against this brazenly political attack.

Preserving the integrity of our armed forces is not a partisan issue.¬†Every Member of Congress took an oath to support the Constitution and that oath compels each of us to push back against the President‚Äôs dangerous attempt to politicize our military.

Name: Cornyn, John
text: On this day in 1945, Cpl. Harlon Block of Weslaco appeared in one of the most indelible images to come out of World War II. For three days the men of Company E, Second Battalion, Twenty-eighth Marines, had fought their way to the top of Mount Suribachi, a 550-foot-high extinct volcano at the southern end of the island of Iwo Jima. @TxStHistAssoc

Name: Cornyn, John
text: They first raised a small flag to signal their victory to their fellows below, and a larger flag later. In Associated Press photographer Joe Rosenthal's picture of the six men raising this second flag, which won the Pulitzer Prize, the twenty-year-old Block was the stooping figure guiding the base of the flagpole into the volcanic ash.

Name: Cornyn, John
text: He never saw the famous picture, however, as he was killed in action on March 1 as his unit advanced in the direction of Mishi Ridge. Block was buried in the Fifth Marine Division cemetery at the foot of Mount Suribachi, though his body was taken home to Weslaco in 1949.

Our wildland firefighters are on the frontlines protecting our communities from increasingly severe wildfires. Yet, instead of providing them with the resources they need, this administration‚Äôs budget freezes and hiring cuts are putting lives, homes, and ecosystems at greater risk.

Prescribed burns reduce fuel for wildfires, but essential projects are being canceled due to frozen funds. The impact? More destructive fires, more devastation, and more danger for our firefighters and communities.

I‚Äôve fought to ensure our federal firefighting force gets the pay, staffing, and resources it needs, including through funding in the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law and Inflation Reduction Act. I‚Äôm continuing to work on bipartisan legislation to modernize our approach to wildfire prevention in the wildland urban interface and beyond. But those funds are now being blocked, leaving our first responders in limbo. We must support our wildland firefighters.

Name: Spartz, Victoria
text:
Why I am a NO on the current version of the house budget instructions - I have a TRILLION DOLLAR QUESTION - where is the money - $1T? 

Interesting FACT: roughly 85% of spending is not ever even looked at by Congress - convenient if you would like to hide waste, fraud and abuse.

I appreciate @chiproytx and @RepArrington for their efforts to move savings from 150B to maybe 200B per year, but even if we take out the 460B increase in social security spending since 2019, even if we adjust the budget for high inflation caused by this outrageous spending (roughly 23% in 5 years), and additional Medicare enrollment of 5M seniors since 2019 adjusted for inflation, we are still about 1.2T per year short = 7T (2024) - ADJ 5.8T (4.5T (2019 spending) + 0.46T (increase in social security) + 0.78T (inflation adjustment for non-social security spending) + 0.08T increase in the number of Medicare recipients adjusted for inflation). If we only search for up to 0.2T, we still have $1 TRILLION per year unexplained. I have a responsibility to the people I represent to find $1T of their hard earned money! 

Some interesting observations: 

1) Federal spending per each Medicare recipient almost doubled in 5 years (about 80% increase per person or additional 500B PER YEAR)! I do not hear from the seniors in my district that quality of it doubled - on the contrary - many complaints about Medicare Advantage, reduction in physician‚Äôs fees and dishonest billing by large hospitals; and 

2) Federal spending per each Medicaid recipient increased more than 60% since the ACA expansion in 2014 (or over 100B per year adjusted for inflation). I also do not hear in my district that the quality of Medicaid significantly increased. On the contrary, people with disabilities,  Medicaid was originally intended for, get less and less services. 

Congress must have answers, since we never even look at this automatic spending.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Knowing they had no credibility, they set up or took over a legion of front groups, to propagate their message from behind the cover of bland or familiar-sounding names. The front groups numbered in the dozens, like keys on a disinformation piano.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: This all began years ago, when a bunch of fossil fuel billionaires saw trouble ahead for their pollution and their pollute-for-free business model, so they began a covert operation to bring industry influence to bear on U.S. politics. Climate denial was born.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The science was clear. Even Exxon‚Äôs scientists knew.¬†The predictions have proven deadly accurate.¬†But when science encounters politics in Congress, politics wins, so fossil fuel went to work to corrupt Congress, deny the science, and mislead the public.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: A covert scheme was also launched to capture and control the Supreme Court, with hundreds of millions more dollars.¬†That seems like a lot, but the payback has been in the tens of billions, particularly for polluters protecting a $700B pollute-for-free subsidy.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: At the same time they ramped up investing in politics, to eradicate any environmental wing in the Republican Party (such as the Chafees of Rhode Island). This power exploded when¬†Citizens United¬†let them offer party leaders unlimited secret ‚Äúdark money.‚Äù

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Republicans got a clear signal: you‚Äôre in with fossil fuel, or you‚Äôre out of the party. (Ask Bob Inglis.) Devilishly clever, that let fossil fuel brand climate change as a partisan issue, not just self-serving special-interest political influence.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The scheme took decades to come to full fruition, with a support network of doctrine factories, ‚Äúamicus‚Äù front groups, fake science, and billionaire donors to reward amenable justices ‚Äî a full judicial-influence ecosystem, much overlapped with climate denial.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Traditional lobbying groups, like the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and National Association of Manufacturers, learned to actively participate in the climate denial operation (likely for big money) or at least stand back and not challenge the lies.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: When Trump was elected, Court capture went into overdrive, with every indication of a deal between Kochs and Trump to hand them Supreme Court (and energy and environment) appointments in return for an end to Koch attacks on Trump.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: With Trump re-elected, the payback to fossil fuel for its financial support is in full view, unashamedly pretending that climate change is a ‚Äúhoax,‚Äù and that electricity from solar and wind is not ‚Äúenergy.‚Äù Decades of lies and corruption were rewarded.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The link between Court capture and climate denial was crystal clear, with Trump‚Äôs counsel bragging that Court capture and deregulation (i.e. pollution regs) were for them ‚Äútwo sides of the same coin.‚Äù¬†That coin was in the polluters‚Äô pocket.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Home insurance is the forerunner of climate‚Äôs economic consequences. Insurance can‚Äôt assess risk in an imaginary future, it has to assess risk in the real world. The insurance business model looking forward is colliding with the fossil fuel industry‚Äôs lies.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Nature, however, doesn‚Äôt care about human lies, corruption or political quid pro quos. She operates by God-given immutable laws of nature that we call physics, chemistry, and biology.¬†So despite the lies, long-predicted dangers are now coming to pass.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Insurance collapse hits mortgage markets, which hits property values, which can lead to general economic collapse.¬†The Fed Chair just warned that in 10-15 years, regions of the U.S. won‚Äôt have mortgages. A $25 trillion real estate hit is predicted globally.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: As Hemingway said about bankruptcies, economic collapses happen ‚Äúgradually, then all at once.‚Äù¬†Look at insurance in Florida, Louisiana and California and you see that we are well into ‚Äúgradually‚Äù; it‚Äôs hard to predict what triggers ‚Äúall at once,‚Äù but it‚Äôs coming.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: When it does, and suffering is widespread, people will care how we got there.¬†We got there because for decades the fossil fuel industry ran, and the Republican Party aided and abetted, the biggest campaign of lies, corruption and disinformation in human history.

Name: Lawler, Michael
text:
Today marks the third anniversary of Russia‚Äôs unprovoked invasion of Ukraine. To be clear: Vladimir Putin is a vile dictator and thug and has committed countless war crimes on his march towards rebuilding the old Soviet Union. He alone is responsible for the devastation that has been wrought over these past three years.                                   

As Ukraine has sought to defend itself and its people, we have rightly supported them. They have fought valiantly in defense of freedom and Democracy ‚Äî ideals Vladimir Putin would never support.

However, this war must come to an end, and a settlement be negotiated that ensures Ukraine‚Äôs sovereignty and lasting peace in the region. In the absence of that, I am concerned about the path forward. If Ukraine falls it will have devastating consequences for Europe, the United States, and the free world.

As negotiations commence, we must be clear-eyed and hold Putin and Russia accountable for their conduct. We must ensure Putin and Russia are removed from Ukraine. And we must ensure stronger economic and national security ties between the United States, and Ukraine as the rebuilding process begins. There is a long road ahead, but I am confident we will be able to bring this war to an end and reassert America‚Äôs role as Leader of the Free¬† World.

This move locks up over 200,000 acres, making it nearly impossible to reduce wildfire risk, thin overgrown forests, or even graze the land. Name: Schiff, Adam B.
text:
Three years ago today, Russia launched a brutal invasion of Ukraine and ignited the worst fighting in Europe since World War II. The Ukrainian people have stood their ground, paying an immense toll to defend their country and democracy.

In response to Russia‚Äôs unprovoked aggression, we have stood shoulder to shoulder with Ukraine. We mobilized unprecedented support and rallied our partners around the world to help preserve Ukraine‚Äôs sovereignty and ensure that Russia does not threaten NATO.

But now, we have a president who is betraying our democratic ally, spouting Kremlin talking points, falsely blaming Ukraine for the war and casting doubt on the legitimacy of President Zelenskyy‚Äôs leadership.

Trump and his team are deliberately undermining Ukraine‚Äôs negotiating position in potential talks with Russia, bringing shame upon the United States and eviscerating our standing in the world.

The U.S. Senate must not yield, must not abandon Ukraine in its hour of greatest need, and must not sew further doubt about America‚Äôs willingness to abide by our commitments to Europe and NATO.

Instead, we must reaffirm our support for Ukraine on a bipartisan basis, continue to provide the crucial assistance that Ukraine needs to defend itself, and work hand-in-hand with our European allies to defend the sovereign rights of all nations.

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
For three long years, the people of Ukraine have fought with extraordinary courage to defend their homeland against Vladimir Putin‚Äôs brutal and unjust invasion. They have never asked for American boots on the ground ‚Äì only the support needed to stand their ground against an invading force determined to erase them from the map.
¬†
When this war began, I met with Ukrainian refugees ‚Äì families forced to flee their homes, many of whom have since found safety and a second home in Massachusetts. I made them a promise that day: that we would stand with our allies. And today, I stand by that promise.
¬†
Ukraine‚Äôs fight is a fight for democracy. A fight for sovereignty. A fight for freedom. And when this war ends ‚Äì when peace is restored ‚Äì it must not be Vladimir Putin who is rewarded for his war of aggression.

Name: McCaul, Michael T.
text:
Three years ago today, Putin sent his army into Ukraine, shattering peace in Europe and threatening global stability. Putin‚Äôs autocratic friends in China, Iran, and North Korea quickly came to his aid, bolstering Russia‚Äôs defense industrial base and sending thousands of troops to fight and kill the Ukrainian people. Make no mistake: This unholy alliance formed by our adversaries seeks to undermine western values, weaken U.S. national security, and upend the global balance of power.

I agree with President Trump that this would never have happened had he been in office. There‚Äôs a reason these hostile regimes did not attack sovereign territories during his first term: He projected peace through strength. All the pain and bloodshed in Europe could have been prevented if Democrats ‚Äî under both the Obama and Biden administrations ‚Äî had stood up to Putin sooner.

This war has raged for three years too many.¬†Putin could stop the killing today, but since he refuses ‚Äî President Trump has answered the call to help put an end to the fighting. As he and his team continue negotiations, I urge them to ensure the agreement holds the Kremlin accountable for its crimes and contains serious teeth to ensure Putin cannot resurrect his quest to recreate the Soviet Union by taking Ukraine. Only then will lasting peace be secured.

In 2023, I announced $1,285,000 in federal funding that I helped secure to repair and enhance Kohler Park in Jim Hogg County. This investment will revitalize one of the only recreational spaces in Hebbronville by improving accessibility, upgrading sports fields and playground equipment, and replacing deteriorated facilities.

The project includes adding accessible sidewalks, shade coverings, bleacher seating, and a new event kiosk, as well as converting the skateboard area from composite board to cement. These enhancements will create a safer, more inclusive space for families and residents of all ages to enjoy.

Encouraging physical activity is essential to improving public health and quality of life. I look forward to seeing this project come to life and the positive impact it will have on the community. I remain committed to securing federal funding for projects that strengthen our communities and promote well-being for all.

She is the Vice President of Student Affairs and Campus Life, an Associate Professor of Psychology, Director of Counseling Services, and Director of the Black Cultural Collection and Resource Center.

Name: Massie, Thomas
text:
I asked Grok if ethanol subsidies and mandates increase food prices. Here‚Äôs Grok‚Äôs answer:

Ethanol mandates and subsidies can indeed push up food prices, and here‚Äôs how it plays out. In the U.S., the Renewable Fuel Standard (RFS) requires blending ethanol‚Äîmostly made from corn‚Äîinto gasoline. Subsidies, like tax credits or direct payments to producers, sweeten the deal for ethanol makers. This jacks up demand for corn, a staple crop for both fuel and food. When more corn gets diverted to ethanol refineries, less is left for livestock feed, processed foods, or export markets. Basic supply and demand kicks in: reduced corn supply for food purposes means higher prices for corn-based products.

Look at the numbers. In 2022, about 40% of U.S. corn production‚Äîroughly 5.3 billion bushels‚Äîwent to ethanol, according to the USDA. That‚Äôs a massive chunk of a crop that also feeds cattle, pigs, and chickens. When corn prices rise‚Äîsay, from $3 a bushel to $7, like they did between 2020 and 2022‚Äîfeed costs for livestock climb too. That ripples through to higher prices for beef, pork, eggs, and dairy at the grocery store. A 2011 National Academy of Sciences study pegged the RFS as bumping corn prices by 20-40% in tight supply years. More recent analyses, like from Iowa State‚Äôs CARD in 2023, suggest ethanol policies still add about 10-15% to corn prices annually, depending on harvest yields and global demand.

It‚Äôs not just corn, either. Land that could grow wheat, soy, or other crops gets planted with corn instead because ethanol keeps corn profitable‚Äîsubsidies have historically pushed corn‚Äôs return per acre above other grains. The USDA says cropland devoted to corn hit 92 million acres in 2023, crowding out alternatives. Less wheat or soy means tighter supplies and higher prices for bread, cooking oil, and tofu too.

On the flip side, ethanol backers argue it‚Äôs not the mandates alone‚Äîglobal factors like weather, oil prices, and trade wars mess with food costs too. They‚Äôre not wrong; the 2022 Ukraine invasion spiked grain prices worldwide, ethanol or not. Plus, ethanol coproducts like distillers‚Äô grains get fed back to livestock, offsetting some feed cost hikes. A 2021 Renewable Fuels Association report claimed this keeps the food price impact under 5%. But that‚Äôs a tough sell when corn prices drive so much of the ag economy‚ÄîUSDA data shows a $1 increase in corn per bushel adds about $0.40 to a pound of retail beef over time.

Globally, it‚Äôs messier. In poorer countries, where people spend 30-50% of income on food (vs. 10% in the U.S.), ethanol-driven grain price jumps hit harder. The 2007-2008 food crisis partly blamed U.S. ethanol policies for spiking corn and tortilla prices in Mexico‚ÄîFAO estimated a 10-15% food price bump there tied to biofuels.

So, yeah, ethanol mandates and subsidies generally nudge food prices up‚Äîhow much depends on harvests, markets, and policy tweaks. Without them, corn might stay cheaper, but gas prices could climb unless oil steps in. It‚Äôs a trade-off: fuel security vs. food affordability. What‚Äôs your take on balancing those?

Name: Massie, Thomas
text:
When I was County Judge Executive in Lewis County Kentucky, I was responsible for signing the check that paid for every phone landline and cellphone billed to the county.

At first it seemed impossible to ferret out the waste, fraud, and abuse for these phone plans.

How many phones were taxpayers paying for that were defunct? How many were former county employees who were no longer employed but had been able to keep their phone and mooch off the taxpayer? Was any of it fraudulent or inaccurate billing by the service provider?

But then I came up with an idea‚Ä¶ I told every county department (Sheriff, Clerk, Road Crew, Jail, etc.) to give me a list of their phones matched to their county employees or offices.

In one month, I would DEACTIVATE EVERY PHONE that wasn‚Äôt on one of these lists.

A month went by and only about 80% complied with the directive to list their phones. I gave them one more month and issued a serious warning that their phones would be turned off at the end of the next month.

Finally, I directed the phone company to deactivate all phones that weren‚Äôt accounted for. Guess what?

The jailer called me up and said the finger print machine wouldn‚Äôt send finger prints to the state police anymore. Ha! That was the only legitimate phone line that I deactivated. We quickly got it reactivated.

I ended up saving our county thousands of dollars on the phone bill, much to the chagrin of the phone company and a few moochers who no longer had free phone plans. I think most of the savings came from phones that just weren‚Äôt in service but had been left on the bill.

Why do I tell this story? Because what Elon is doing by asking federal employees to list five things they did in a week is brilliant. Requiring any kind of an affirmative response from a worker will prove whether that worker even exists and can be reached. Don‚Äôt forget, the Inspector General for Afghanistan found out we were paying millions for soldiers and police in Afghanistan who didn‚Äôt even exist (ghost employees). There‚Äôs no telling what Elon‚Äôs plan will uncover. We will find some employees can‚Äôt use email or aren‚Äôt even literate enough to write five things. So everyone take a chill pill and write down your five things to let us know you exist and you can read email and you aren‚Äôt completely insubordinate. Then we can clean the roster.

text:
‚ùìQuestion: Can Congress impeach judges for flagrantly partisan or corrupt rulings?

üî¥ Answer: Yes. Alexander Hamilton wrote about this matter in Federalist 65. He suggested that the subjects of impeachments "are those offenses which proceed from the misconduct of public men, or, in other words, from the abuse or violation of some public trust. They are of a nature which may with peculiar propriety be denominated political, as they relate chiefly to injuries done immediately to the society itself."

Each of the judges with impeachment articles drafted against them has violated the public's trust by overtly targeting President Trump and his administration. Their rulings are intended to be politically undermining and nothing else.

In the case of Judge Bates, he is forcing taxpayers to pay for the publication and endorsement of chemical castration on government websites. This decision is sickening and a gross abuse of his bench.
